loomCode:
theme { skin:"brutalist", layout:"wide", density:"comfortable" }

hero
  title:"Nested Parallel Processing"
  subtitle:"3 departments × 10 employees = 30 concurrent lanes. All scored simultaneously."
  size:"md"
  align:"left"

section padding:"lg" background:"subtle" {
  columns cols:3 gap:"lg" {
    card padding:"md" border:"strong" {
      heading level:3 "Depth 0 — Single Lane"
      text "One execution. Generates all company data, then assembles the final report once all departments are done. Nodes — Generate Company Data and Build Company Report."
    }
    card padding:"md" border:"strong" {
      heading level:3 "Depth 1 — 3 Department Lanes"
      text "The runtime sees List[Dept] flowing into a Dept port and expands into 3 parallel lanes automatically — one per department. Nodes — Extract Department Info and Summarize Department."
    }
    card padding:"md" border:"strong" {
      heading level:3 "Depth 2 — 30 Employee Lanes"
      text "Inside each department lane, List[Employee] expands again into 10 more lanes. All 30 employee lanes run at the same time. Node — Score Employee (x30 concurrent)."
    }
  }

  spacer size:"sm"

  card padding:"md" border:"subtle" {
    heading level:3 "Broadcasting"
    text "The scoring config lives at depth 0. The runtime broadcasts it to all 30 employee lanes automatically — no extra wiring needed. A depth-1 value like department name is broadcast only to the 10 lanes within that department, not across departments."
  }

  spacer size:"sm"

  card padding:"md" border:"subtle" {
    heading level:3 "Gather and Null Propagation"
    text ```
**Gather** is the inverse of expand. When a T port flows into a List[T] port, the runtime collects all parallel lanes back into a single list — one item per lane. Expand and gather always pair 1-1, every expand has exactly one corresponding gather downstream.

If a lane produces null (invalid data, a node that returns nothing), the lane does not disappear — it carries null forward. The inner gather collects 10 employee lanes per department and produces a List[Employee | Null]. The department summary node then filters out nulls before computing scores. The same applies at depth 1 — if a department lane produces null, the outer gather includes it as null in the final list, and the report node filters it out.

Filter nulls after gathering, not before. The gather always produces a complete list with one slot per original lane.
    ```
  }
}

divider

columns cols:2 gap:"xl" align:"stretch" {
  card padding:"lg" border:"strong" {
    heading level:3 "Scoring Config"
    text "Tune the three parameters used to score every employee across all 30 lanes. Changes take effect on the next run."
    field scoring_config value
      as:textarea
      height:"200px"
      label:"JSON Config"
      description:"base_per_skill: points per skill · experience_multiplier: bonus per year of experience · senior_threshold: minimum years to be counted as senior"
  }

  card padding:"lg" border:"subtle" {
    heading level:3 "Scoring Formula"
    text "Each employee is scored as: skill_score = skill_count x base_per_skill, exp_bonus = years x experience_multiplier, total_score = skill_score + exp_bonus, is_senior = years >= senior_threshold."
    spacer size:"sm"
    text "Diversity tier is assigned by skill count: Expert means 5 or more skills, Versatile means 3 to 4 skills, Specialist means 1 to 2 skills."
    spacer size:"sm"
    text "Department efficiency is measured as budget divided by total_score. Lower is more efficient."
  }
}

cta label:"Run Pipeline" action:"run" size:"lg" align:"center"

divider

output report_output data
  as:markdown
  height:"75vh"
  label:"Company Report"
  placeholder:"Run the pipeline to generate the full talent report — per-department breakdowns, employee rankings, and efficiency metrics."

spacer size:"md"

output stats_output data
  as:json
  height:"40vh"
  label:"Company Stats (JSON)"
  placeholder:"Aggregated statistics will appear here after the run."

footer note:"Nested parallel processing demo · 3 departments · 10 employees · 30 concurrent lanes"
